title: Gwen & Art Are Not in Love
author: Croucher, Lex*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: listen!!! i do not do romance. as an aro dyke with more than a little romance repulsion, it just ends in frustration if i go there. i ALSO do not do hlisten!!! i do not do romance. as an aro dyke with more than a little romance repulsion, it just ends in frustration if i go there. i ALSO do not do historical fiction. when my friend put this book in my hands i gave her major side-eye but decided to roll with it because in 3 years of book recs she has not once steered me wrong, and holy shit, i am so glad i trusted her. this had it all-- the friendship, the banter, the enemies to friends to [hard stop, NOT lovers], the riverdale and mary oliver references, a sexy butch knight flirting with the princess with her sword. the plot did not once sacrifice the friendships for the romantic pairings, and i want to fling myself at the author's feet and thank them for that specifically and profusely. almost none of the tropes that frustrate me with romance cropped up in this book. there were like, three chapters where i wanted to pull my hair out and yell IF YOU WOULD JUST HAVE A CONVERSATION-- but it lasted those three (3) chapters and that's it. incredible. the "historical" side of things is played very fast and loose, and i adore it. feels camp, feels queer, feels very "fuck your rules."if you love romance, you will probably like this novel, because it is very smartly written and has lovable characters and a satisfying ending and everyone who gets paired off legitimately has chemistry instead of just getting smashed together to fulfill some sort of true love quota.if you do not love (or even like) romance, you will probably still enjoy this novel, because the friendships here are what get to shine. so, from one romance-repulsed aromantic allosexual queer to whomever is reading this  ... this YA romcom gets my highest queerplatonic recommendation. there is SUCH a multiplicity of relationships on display in this novel, and it's truly wonderful. i've never been so delighted to be so wrong about a book....more

review: miller tends to whiplash from mishap to mishap rather than holding the reins of his own plot (a complaint i had with rogue elements, too), but he's stmiller tends to whiplash from mishap to mishap rather than holding the reins of his own plot (a complaint i had with rogue elements, too), but he's stellar when it comes to banter and really knows his star trek lore. while i have an entire skeleton of bones to pick re: sticking una with a r*mantic arc (and with a man) (god) (i pretend i do not see it), that too feels classically star trek ("meridian" and "tomorrow and tomorrow and tomorrow," i'm looking at y'all). aside from that bit of nonsense, i enjoyed myself with this one. i do not understand the decision for the narrative to refer to una as "chin-riley" the entire goddamn book rather than "una" or "number one," but it wouldn't be a star trek pocket book if it didn't make an incomprehensible decision or two.tl;dr: a fun time if you don't mind an excess of pike chapters, are a horse girl, love uhura, wish la'an and hemmer had interacted more, and don't mind spock and m'benga getting reduced to bit roles while ortegas is barely there and chapel isn't to be seen at all. definitely one of the better star trek novels, and i'll be tracking down the enterprise war in the hopes that una doesn't have to kiss a dude in that one...more

review: stellar. my ideal blend of personal narrative + cultural analysis, the kind of thing i've been hankering for without quite realizing it. williams doesstellar. my ideal blend of personal narrative + cultural analysis, the kind of thing i've been hankering for without quite realizing it. williams does such a great job of tipping and turning the source material so that all its facets catch the light and what you end up with is a portrait of a movie far too complex to boil down into a single thing. "james baldwin sees the exorcist" was my favorite chapter. i highly recommend tracking down his essay on the experience as detailed in the devil finds work and reading it alongside this one. i also recommend s. trimble's essay "a demon-girl's guide to life" in it came from the closet for a queer reading of the film. tl;dr i highly recommend this book if you're a lover of horror, essays, or thoughtful blends of pop culture analysis, historical context, and memoir. i don't even LIKE the exorcist and i couldn't put this down. as a writer, creative nonfiction is my chosen genre, and while i've strayed from it these past few years, this book made me want to go back to it. at the end of the day, that's all i can ask of a piece of media. that it points me back toward home....more

review: it's very white, which is unavoidable due to the prohibitive cost of deep-sea exploration and the extremely cishet white male makeup of the submersiblit's very white, which is unavoidable due to the prohibitive cost of deep-sea exploration and the extremely cishet white male makeup of the submersible industry. however, i wish she had interrogated that whiteness and richness a lot more. there are mentions of the effects of colonialism, of ancient indigenous knowledge of things white people "discovered" only recently, of groups that are fighting to counteract climate change, of a lot of other things that could have been developed into a clear portrait of exactly who has been fucking up the ocean all these years and who has been steadily working to counteract these damages, but it doesn't go beneath the surface of that, and that's my one critique. aside from that, holy shit. i loved this. could not put it down, set aside all my other books, binged it, stayed up past bedtime, etc etc. highly recommend if you wanna cry about the ocean. also, "the ocean as metaphor for queerness" factor is just....................,,,, off the charts in this book...more

title: Sounds Fake But Okay: An Asexual and Aromantic Perspective on Love, Relationships, Sex, and Pretty Much Anything Else
author: Costello, Sarah
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: frustrating!!!! for a book that talks about the split-attraction model so much, they really do Not account for the allosexual aromantic perspective atfrustrating!!!! for a book that talks about the split-attraction model so much, they really do Not account for the allosexual aromantic perspective at ALL. i picked this book up because even though i've reached a saturation point with my research into asexuality, it had the word "aromantic" in the subtitle, and it is really really really hard to find aromantic content, even harder to find aromantic content without asexual content overshadowing it.i had cautious hopes for this book, and it did not deliver on that front. asexuality overshadows aromanticism at every turn, and the only time aromanticism is discussed is if it's paired with asexuality. very, very frustrating for someone like me who spent years researching asexuality at the expense of aromanticism bc i just...didn't have enough exposure to aromantic content to realize i WAS aromantic romance-repulsed. absolutely wild time to get to age 28 and realize you've been looking at the Wrong end of the spectrum the entire time, largely because aspec spaces pay way more attention to asexuality than they do aromanticism. idk if that's just because there's fewer of us allo aros out there, or because the possibility of alloaro-ism hasn't even occurred to us due to [checks notes] all the things i've touched on in this , but whatever the reason, i'm #tired and more than a little bit irritated too.still worth reading if you're new to aspec perspectives, but don't go into this one expecting anything radical. to be clear, i am not faulting the authors too much here. yes, they could have done a better job gathering aromantic perspectives. but they're also inventing a genre as they go here, and there's only so much you can expect from pioneers before you've got to roll up your sleeves and (unfortunately) create the content you wish to see in the world yourself. aspec lit is still very much in its infancy, and while i'm so grateful it even has a space to exist, i'm still so frustrated by the limited range of it all. we are still having to cater so hard to amatonormative sensibilities. i wish i could fast-forward 30 years to see the future of the genre, just so i can come back here and endure this entry-level "we promise we're not that super weird" stage with a little more grace....more

review: I am really enjoying this golden age of the fragmented novel/book. This one was a bit TOO fragmented for me, but there were times I really got into thI am really enjoying this golden age of the fragmented novel/book. This one was a bit TOO fragmented for me, but there were times I really got into the rhythm of it. Ultimately, reading on a screen kind of dimmed it for me. I think a tactile book might have left more of an impression. EDIT UPON PHYSICAL REREAD: I was correct. This is a stunner, and I will be rereading it multiple times, I am sure, as I continue to collage my own book together. I love how it built on itself.
